Slide 1 — Title
Extending Monitoring Agent: Chat Interface Design Options

Objective
Enable conversational monitoring over:

Job execution
Agent workflows
PR generation outcomes

Scope

Extend existing Upload → Agent → PR pipeline
Add conversational interface powered by AgentCore
Slide 2 — Current Architecture (Baseline)
Existing System Overview

Flow

User → Upload API (EC2)
Files → S3
Job → DynamoDB
Submit Lambda → Agent Execution Lambda
AgentCore → GitHub PR
Job Status Lambda → UI polling

Key Strength

Clear async pipeline
Strong separation of concerns
Already job-driven architecture (good for chat extension)
Slide 3 — Problem Statement
What’s Missing

Users currently:

See job status only
Cannot interact with system
Cannot ask:
Why did this fail?
What changed?
What PR was generated?
What is the root cause?
Opportunity

Introduce Monitoring Agent Chat to:

Explain system behavior
Assist debugging
Provide insights across jobs + artifacts
Slide 4 — Design Options Overview
Two Approaches
Option	Description	Persistence
Option 1	Full Chat System	Permanent (DynamoDB)
Option 2	Copilot-style Assistant	Temporary (in-memory)
Slide 5 — Option 1: Persistent Chat
Concept

A full chat system:

Conversations stored in DynamoDB
Restored on refresh
Supports long-running investigations
User Flow
Open chat
Start or resume conversation
Ask questions about jobs
Agent uses:
Job DB
S3
AgentCore memory
Responses saved permanently
Slide 6 — Option 1 Architecture (Narrative)
Extended Flow
Chat UI → Next.js API
API:
Stores messages in DynamoDB
Fetches history
Calls Monitoring Agent
Agent:
Reads job state (DynamoDB)
Reads artifacts (S3)
Uses AgentCore memory
Response:
Stored in DB
Returned to UI
New Components
Chat APIs
Chat DynamoDB tables
Monitoring AgentCore agent
